`` The industry is still pretty much in its <ENAMEX TYPE="LOC">Wild West</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">days</ENAMEX> , '' says <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Scott Stapf</ENAMEX> , director of investor education for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">the North American Securities Administrators Association</ENAMEX> .
An admittedly limited survey by <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG">NASAA</ENAMEX> , whose members are state securities - law regulators , found that <ENAMEX TYPE="DATE">between 1986 and 1988</ENAMEX> `` fraud and abuse '' by financial planners cost <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">22,000</ENAMEX> investors <ENAMEX TYPE="MONEY">$ 400 million</ENAMEX> .
The rogues ' gallery of planners involved includes some convicted felons , a compulsive gambler or <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">two</ENAMEX> , various businessmen who had planned their own previous ventures right into bankruptcy , and <ENAMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">one</ENAMEX> man who scammed his wife 's grandmother .
